This paper deals with information-theoretic security in communication channels, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of information theory (cs.IT). The paper specifically focuses on interference and broadcast channels, which are commonly studied in the subfield of communication (cs.COMM). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of random binning techniques, which are often used in cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also mentions the use of Gaussian interference channels, which are commonly studied in the subfield of signal processing (cs.MM). Finally, the paper discusses the use of artificial noise in transmission schemes, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of security and privacy (cs.SI).
